Loan Data Exploration¶

by Yaron Shamash¶

Investigation Overview¶

This document explores a dataset containing loan amounts, borrower information, and interest rates for approximately 114,000 loans. The goal of this presentation is to find out what variables impact a borrowers rate they pay on a loan. I initially thought loan amount would play a big role in the rate the borrower receives, but there were a few other variables that made bigger impacts.

Dataset Overview¶

There are 113,937 rows and 81 columns in the data set. The characteristics of the variables in the data set include dtypes: bool(3), category(1), float64(50), int64(11), object(17).

Note that the above cells have been set as "Skip"-type slides. That means that when the notebook is rendered as http slides, those cells won't show up.

Relationship between Loan Amount vs Borrower Rate¶

Interest rates for the lower loan amounts tend have a wider range than the rates on Loan Amounts at the higher end. The highest loan amounts have some of the lowest interest rates. Opposite my initial thought. The most common loan is 5k at an interest rate of about 0.32. There also seems to be many loans at $15k with and interest rate of 0.2.

Relationship between DebtToIncomeRatio and BorrowerRate¶

The Borrower Rate starts to increase at about 0.4 Debt to Income Ratio. At Debt to Income Ratio of over 0.5, the BorrowerRate is almost 0.2 and higher. Borrowers should try to keep their Debt to Income Ratio below 0.4.

Bivariate plot of DebttoIncomeRatio and ProsperRating¶

Lower debt to income results in higher rating.

Multivariate plot of OpenRevolvingMonthlyPayment and CurrentDelinquencies¶

Although debt to income negatively corresponds to the borrower rate, higher monthly payments dont necessarily mean more delinquencies.

Multivariate plot of Prosper Rating and BorrowerRate by loan Term¶

For most borrowers, shorter loan terms means lower rates.

Multivariate plot of DebttoIncome ratio BankcardUtilization and BorrowerRate¶

One sure fire way to keep the borrower's rate low is to keep bank card utilization below 0.2, and the Debt to Income Ratio below 0.3
